Czech discovery: a substance that also works with stolen HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works in viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the connection to common virus variants is not as strong as one of the drugs already available.
AIDS cannot yet be cured.
However, patients can prolong their life and prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a whole series of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus reproduction also results in the development of so-called resistant viruses against which medicines are no longer effective.
The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSCT (Chemisch-Technological University) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to how to deal with the virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances referred to as metalocarborans have an effect on the protein that is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
The metalocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus proliferation in a different way than all medicines used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists get to new ́improved ́ compounds, which were prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two versatile cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Home-like and persistent virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus spread caused by the HIV protease, mature infectious virus particles would not occur.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed.
A bit weaker but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances on the HIV protease was tested in the reagent glass, including their resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metalocarborane on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as that of the clinically used medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants that the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical designs, makes metalocarborans interesting compounds for further research on the development of effective anti-HIV drugs, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
