New vaccination
Vaccines free for August children
From January onwards, children can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococcals born on August 2, last year and later.
The condition is that they have not received a vaccination dose yet.
Anyone who has started vaccination last year or earlier must also pay for further revaccination himself.
The first dose of the vaccine must be given between the 3rd and 5th months of life of the child.
Last year, a quarter of the families had their children vaccinated against pneumococcal disease.
The parents paid 1600 crowns and more for a dose.
Four doses are required for the vaccination of the youngest children.
Overall, experts estimate that health insurances spend 300,000 to 450,000 crowns per year for the vaccine doses.
But they save on the treatment that the children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 per year on all children's surface vaccinations.
The mandatory acceptance was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococci cause middle ear inflammation, but also severe infections including meningitis and blood poisoning.
Through pneumococcal infections, up to 28 children up to 10 years of age die from examinations in hospitals every year.
Outside the Czech Republic, the compulsory reception of children against pneumococcal disease was introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
As of January, these are to be paid and voluntary by the insurance companies.
For example, the head of Nahlas, Rudolf Kalovsky, mentioned that the mandatory reception would be better.
