Tawa hallae looked like many other meat-eating dinosaurs: The two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-long animal ran on two strong hind legs, had a long skull with sharp, bent teeth, short arms with silky claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa haloae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was at that time in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window for the early evolution of the dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging on Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaurs in a day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, reports team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional find: "Dinosaur fossils from the trias are extremely rare, usually only single pieces are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
The dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago after the current lesson.
Many of the oldest fossils, however, are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these original dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts discuss when the echsen split into their three main development lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor, and also the birds, the four-legged souropods known as "long-necks" and their relatives, and the plants-eating ornithischia (Vogelbecksauries), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues Tawa hugae is an original theropod.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
At the skull of Tawa hallae, the researchers found, for example, evidence of airbags, as well as the descendants of the Theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of the birds is more efficient than that of the mammals.
At Tawa haloae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge Sauropods later also had air bags and lightweight knuckles, probably the common ancestors of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the Echsen appeared there for the first time.
As a result, the three development lines split early and spread from South America over all parts of the earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass as supercontinent Pangea.
For this, the fact that the team together with Tawa hallae found the remains of two more, not particularly closely related theropods.
