75 % of working mothers have problems at work due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of CSIC's study "Fructility and Career of Women in Spain" conducted in cooperation with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of employed women see their career opportunities limited on the labour market due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to set up a family and the number of children depending on whether the women work or not, and if so, what kind of profession they practice.
Those of them who do not perform any other activity outside the house, only work half day or have no fixed contract of employment, are more likely to be mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with fixed-term employment, especially in the public sector, are moving away from the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore also have fewer children.
"Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed-term employment only get their first child on average 3.7 years after the date of marriage, a figure which increases to 4.1 years for women with fixed-term employment who have needed longer to achieve this and who have only realized the first child much later.
Furthermore, the type of work also has a major influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar of conception," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account at the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, age at the time of marriage and the first child is all the higher, the higher the educational level.
This difference could also be found in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they have only primary education or higher education, became mothers on average with 25.1 or 32.1 for the first time.
Moreover, depending on the level of education, there is a further difference between women.
While the women with the main degree already marry before their first permanent position and get their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree make it exactly the other way around and seek a permanent position and marry afterwards and then get their first child, Delgado notes.
