Support for brake manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the anti-lock braking system ABS, and as is currently the case with the stability control ESP, the auxiliary braking systems have to become mandatory in European cars in case of emergency.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly approved passenger cars and light-duty small transporters, for which the remaining vehicles have a period of grace until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measures adopted by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but due to their operation, these braking systems can also help prevent many road accidents.
The emergency brake assister's task is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical brake manoeuvre which detects the system on the brake pedal using the brake force carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to a study commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not stopped with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, reaches the braking system with maximum force and thereby reduces the braking time and thus the braking distance that a car places in the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assist.
There would be even fewer accidents - one expects that every fourth accident could be prevented with personal damage - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (through radar or camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, the system will help him increase pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
